m babies.  Those people have far more opportunities to get far better stuff from their guild raids.  If they're going to help CoG, they should be altruistic about it.  It's kind of like people donating to charity for the sole purpose of getting the charitable tax deduction.  Thats not altruism.<br><br>Though I don't think the loot should be level-restricted.  I think it should be restricted on the person's guild and what other Kunark dragon rotations they're in.  Kunark dragons drop the same stuff.  If they have another source for the loot via the Kunark dragon rotations then they should not loot from Vox/Naggy.  Vox and Naggy KCoG raids are the only source for epic pieces etc. for people in guilds that aren't in any rotations.  Lets give the little guys a fair chance.<br><br><br><br> <p>-- --<BR><b><i>The Right Reverend Palanka, Th.D.</i></b><BR>High Priest of Truth, Karana Server.  <a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=119628">Magelo Profile</a><BR></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/upalankakarana.showPublicProfile?language=EN>PalankaKarana</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.tripod.co.uk/redhotant/icons/iconoc01.gif" BORDER=0> at: 6/30/02 12:19:22 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/urreddd.showPublicProfile?language=EN>rreddd</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 12:15:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: KCoG dragon support groups</span><hr size=1> As I understand further, only one of the three paladins who was in the support group rolled on book (none actually dropped)  but... there were two people there with paladin alts trying to roll!  That blows my mind.  They brought the paladins to roll but did not play the paladin for the fight!<br><br>Is this against the rules?  (they didn't win the roll and as I said, no book dropped) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulogan42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Logan42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 12:19:13 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Support Groups</span><hr size=1> Well, let me say this.  I don't have a problem with support groups being able to roll on items, as long as it doesn't get out of hand.  Unfortunately I think that at some point you have to admit that.  In their defense though for example on the paladin book there were 3 paladins that came to help with support group, and only one paladin actually rolled.  The other two 53+ paladins came not even taking a chance at getting the book.  On the other side of the coin I noticed a bit of a disturbing trend that I kind of took exception to, and that was that some people were bringing people to raid, and then logging onto another class (paladins) to roll for their epic items.  I don't really agree with that, and didn't really like that at all.  But I (as a temp raid leader) decided not to rock the boat over it, and so let it pass.  Personally, I do come on these raids for fun, I don't expect to win items, and I do expect to die.  For instance tonight I did not even roll on anything (though the rezz stick was tempting).  If you are coming along just for loot or epic drops (and some of you were pretty blunt about saying so), then do not come.  I think that I speak for the majority of people that come for a good time by all that if all you are coming for is the drops then don't come, we don't need you.  <br><br>Come for fun, or not at all.  If you happen to win an item, that is just gravy.  That is what KCoG is all about, and I think that you are right that some people have lost that direction. <br><br>Just my two cents, Don't take it personally as it is just my opinions.<br><br>Farrnusno<br>Guild Leader<br>Souls of the Valiant <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulagdalentarcho.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lagdalen Tarcho</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoG Companion</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 12:52:43 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.engtong.com/Valoran/images/60x60/lagdalen60x60.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Support Groups</span><hr size=1> Since I'm the one that started the &quot;support groups can roll&quot; thing, leme explain why I did it back then.<br><br>Just after SB had stepped down from leading there was obviously a fear of a new leader. Those being Flarren and I with support from FoF. We had many discussions with higher enders and came to the conclusion that killing the dragon itself would be alot easier if we had access to the higher end buffs. That meant a support group. It also meant that people wouldn't be as fearful if there was possibly a stick cleric on hand, you see the benefits.<br><br>Now the support group back then usually consisted of 1 to 2 groups of lvl 60's. Each one had a specific purpose in being there and they were a great deal of help in the long run. btw if you've never killed a dragon without 53+ help, I suggest you give it a shot sometimes and enjoy your zerg or fail. <br><br>Now along with allowing them to go I had to at least make it worth their while, afterall how can you ask someone to come help you with nothing in return. So they were offered a chance to roll. It was also expected that if they already had a shot at that loot or if they had a chance to get better that they did NOT roll and instead let a raider get it. Most of the support people that helped on my runs never lottoed but we were always grateful for their presence.<br><br>Wether they got in the fight or not is inconcequental when you look at what they help you to do. Dragon raids used to be on average 7hrs+ EVERY time. Now they are down to what... 4hrs?<br><br>Perhapse it's time the rules were revised, who knows. I dont lead the runs anymore so it's not my call. I am telling you why I allowed them to roll in the first place and I believe very strongly that if they were un needed on the raids, they would have been asked to leave and denied loot a long time ago.<br><br>The people who have no buisness on the runs are the greedy loot whoreish arses who show up regularily. There is an easy way to solve this though. If they cannot benefit the raid to an acceptable ammount (ex. lvl 60 pallie that has BMB) dont take them for support group. If the person is 53 and just wants a shot, too bad, they dont have anything to contribute more then a 52 could. THAT is how my support groups were... but as some of you may remember I was a biatch sometimes anyway and everyone knew it <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START ;) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/wink.gif ALT=";)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  Limit your lvl to like 55+ only or, useful classes only or something and you'll find you drop the deadbeat jerks and get the people that really do want to help.<br><br><br>PS. I'm damn glad this isn't my decision anymore though heh, good luck Azure *HUGS* <p><center> <img src=http://www.telusplanet.net/public/flarren/Lagdalen.gif> </center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unamiena.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Namiena</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 1:40:35 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: KCoG dragon support groups</span><hr size=1> I have to agree here about how the support groups are getting out of hand. Tonight was a prime example, I noticed someone I knew (not mentioning names here) inc for the raid. Now already knowing that there was like 14 or more support peeps including an epic cleric, I asked him why is he inc with his 60 warrior and cleric (forget lvl). LOL and he said 'loots'. Then went on to tell me how he needed an RBB and his cleric could use the eyepatch and white scale. I said that is typical greed, and he cant roll with both his toons. Well to make a long story short he started cussing me out (which was was reported and petitioned on) and put on ignore. Then he got on 2 other toons to send me tells and harrass me more. It's crazy!! Then I hear that someone was complaining in chat that 'his' guild can do vox in 3 hours, well excuse me, but why is someone here when his guild is on vox rotation? And for pally's to log on just to roll for the book then not even play those toons is way out of line.  IMHO 1 group of support is sufficent for the dragons, and I do believe they should be able to roll on something for all their help. But then again, if they are in a guild that is capable of and is on rotation for dragons, should they really take away from the people that cant? You know what I do is on sign ups, I sign up Teressa my 51 monk, then state that I have a lvl 60 epic cleric if needed for support. That way the raid leader can see who is signed up for support and can determine what classes are needed to make a good strong support group. CoG was never about the loots, but the thrill of taking targets down for people that dont have that oppertunity. I would hate to see that change  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <p>Abreanna Darkangel <br>60 Cleric</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/unamiena.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Namiena</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif" BORDER=0> at: 6/30/02 2:08:14 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/bcouncilofguilds.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=varalla>Varalla</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 5:03:20 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://sdg6.homestead.com/files/ICON.GIF WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: KCoG dragon support groups</span><hr size=1> Interisting.<br><br>Here be me scoop on all of this.<br>Back in March I think I got invited to do a Naggy raid.<br>I nae ever even dreamed I would get an opportunity to fight one.<br><br>Twas Azure that let me go and I didnae even know what the Dragons drop.<br>(I had considered dragons WELL beyond me reach)<br><br>Thankie to the KCoG I had a second opportunity to fight Naggy, and last night Vox.<br><br>Now that I be 53 again I had planned on coming to support.<br>(Although from what I read I'm nae really needed yet, so Ill level to 55 first)<br><br>Why?<br>I'm nae really big on the loot and do nae really care for any giant XP.<br>(I got me Seb key for Heavens sake)<br><br>I plan on doing it because I appreciated how KCoG made it possible for me to fight these Dragons and I wannae continue to be apart of it.<br><br>Im going to have to say me opinion be support shouldnt roll.<br>If they need an incentive then they nae supporting the spirit of what it be all about.<br>In me eyes anyway I do nae know much about KCoG, but when I hit 55 I plan on coming and supporting because I wannae be apart of what I see as special.<br>Let the youngsters have the loot.<br>To date the Dragon raids Ive been on have been me high point of the game.<br>I do nae need an incentive to help out those who brought me those high points.<br><br>--=(ßaroness Varalla Griƒƒinsbane)=--<br>53 Champion of the Shadowstormers <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/useisekerrswiftstrike.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Seisekerr Swiftstrike</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 6:42:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: KCoG dragon support groups</span><hr size=1> Well I already talked to the original poster, but ill say it here too.<br><br>Ill admit it, I came on the raid for white scale -- not the only reason -- but a big factor. I brought my bard to Vox to speed up buffing and killing of giants. Succeeded with both of those. I think if you come and help, you should be included in rolls, but mainly just epic ones. I know some people who joined the raid to roll on RBB etc. I think thats ok, but there were way to many people there just for the loot.<br><br>FYI my guild isnt on any dragon rotations. <p><center><img src=http://seisekerr.freewebspace.com/avanteenigmas.jpg><br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=84680">Seisekerr Swiftstrike</a> -- Master of the Celestial Fists<br><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=102119">Avante Vires`Fortitudo</a> -- Virtuoso of the Wind<br><i>Karana Server</i><br></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uhavykokenasmyl.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Havyk Okenasmyl</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 12:19:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: KCoG dragon support groups</span><hr size=1> Typically the 53+ support group works their butt off on these raids, and makes them go a heck of a lot smoother. However, you don't need 2-3+ support groups, you need one good one. If you have 20 people level 53+ show up, then the raid leader should pick six of them that are going to help the most, and then tell the rest of them thanks for your support and goodnight. Now having said that, I personally think that members of the support group should be allowed to roll on loot, given their contribution to the overall raid. <br><br>I certainly don't agree with people switching to alts just to roll on a piece of loot. The ONLY case where this should be allowed is if someone wants to bring one character, but the raid leader specifically asks them to bring a different character to make the raid a success. In those cases, that person is still only allowed to roll on one of their toons. If you allow people to roll for alts that don't participate in the raid, you might as well just let everyone roll on everything. <p><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51270"><img src="http://home.insightbb.com/~davidfinley815/newSigSmall03.jpg" border="0"></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uladyazureskye.showPublicProfile?language=EN>LadyAzureSkye</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/black_magentaspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Lady of the Mist</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 1:38:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=10>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Support Team and Raids</span><hr size=1> &lt;pulls out her soapbox&gt;<br>Sit down because this is going to be one long post. <br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> But</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->,you will not find anything like it on this forum. Definately a must read.<br><br>------------------------------------------------------------<br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Why we need a Support Team</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Most raiders don't see what goes on behind the scenes. The pathway to a Dragon's Lair is not easy. It takes knowledge and experienced raiders to clear and pull the lair.<br><br><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Vox</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>There are 2 Ice Giants that spawn every 30 minutes.There are 9 Ice Giants, 2 spiders, and 2 icy terrors that are on a 3 hour spawn timer.There are pits leading up to and surrounding her lair. Pits with bears, wolves, spiders, and icy terrors, just waiting for a snack.<br>And we've just gotten to the lair. Inside you find 4 Ice Giants, 1 Fire Giant (Naggy's priest), 2 icy terrors, and Lady Vox. All except Vox are also on a 3 hour spawn timer. If a level 52 or under goes into Vox's lair.. chance are they will die. If a level 53 or higher goes into Vox's lair... they may die from Ice Giants etc..but Vox cannot touch them. If any mob in the lair sees them, she banishes them from the Zone. Yes they end up in Everfrost just outside the Permafrost zone. So besides pulling the lair, timing is the biggest factor. If the lair is pulled too early, it could mean all those baddies popping on top of the buffline, or during Corpse Retrieval. And sometime Corpse Retrieval is done with Vox still alive. Ice Giants repopping is NOT a pretty sight.<br><br><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><u>Nagafen</u><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END--><br>From the zone in to Sol B, raiders may have to pass kobolds, sonic bats, lava duct crawlers, beetles, and stone spiders. Depending on if these are camped or not, the actually raiders will usually have to clear as they go due to spawn rates. Once we reach the Fire Giant areas (they are tougher than Ice Giants) there are 15 Fire Giants, including King Tranix and Warlord Skarlon. Inside the Lair is 3 Fire Giants and Lord Nagafen. One of the Fire Giants is right behind Naggy (kissing up Im sure). Same rules here for Dragon Aggro. Under level 53 is slaughtered, over level 53 is banished to outside the zone. All Fire Giants are on a 7-8 hour spawn timer. So killing them during a raid, we usually don't worry about Fire Giant repops. BUT there have been times when we have gone in and most of the Fire Giants are dead (even though there is a rule that the guilds on our server have promised to follow about NOT killing FG's if Nagafen is up. More people need to be educated about it). Who killed them? When did they kill them? Will they respawn during raiding, buffing, etc? Nice to have a support team to deal with any unexpected repops.<br><br>Support team does ALOT more than sit on the wrong ramps to Vox's lair. They risk as much, if not more, than those actually killing the dragon. They clear the path, keep it clear, time repops, and do Corpse Retrieval. After a total wipeout, a good support team can make the difference between a 5 hour Corpse Retrieval and a 1 hour Corpse Retrieval.<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Buffline</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Most of our buffline consists of actual raiders. Occasionally we are graced with higher levels and thier buffs, summoned items, and mana songs. Many do not think buffs are too important. Dragons dispell. Why it is important to get your buffs in the proper order. Do you want your HP buff dispelled first? I think not. Getting the proper buffs and in the correct order are crucial to the outcome of a raid.<br><br>------------------------------------------------------------<br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Trust. Respect. Attitude</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Trust</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>When you go on a raid, you put your trust in that raid leader. If they say &quot;Charge!&quot; you do even if you don't agree or understand why. If you don't have that trust, then don't go on the raid. <br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Respect</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Respect all those around you. Two types of repsect. One is given freely and the other is earned. <br>Respect given freely is giving someone the benefit of the doubt, being aware of others feelings, treating that person as a human being even if you don't agree completely with what they are saying or doing.<br>Respect earned is entirely between the two people involved. It is earned thru words and actions, or lack thereof. It is earned thru upholding values.<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Attitude</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Your attitude does not just affect you. It affects all you come in contact with. Attitude can be just your being in general or it can be focused at a cetain item, situation, or person. <br><br>These three attributes have always been a concern to me, in and out of the game, in all my dealings.<br><br>Different people, different opinions, different perspectives, different goals. I would like to think that all who come on KCoG raids have the same goal. But I am fully aware that is not the case. There is nothing wrong with having different priorities and goals. But to accomplish what you desire from the game you need to be with those who have the same goals, attitudes, and focus, as your own. <br>If you are not here to have fun, meet your fellow Karanians, and experience the thrill of working together to take down a dragon, then go somewhere else.<br><br>-----------------------------------------<br>All that being said, I would like to address the comments and concerns of this post.<br>I do believe that people took advantage of a substitute raid leader last night. I was there mainly as an observer and organizing the buffline. I observed alot of comments and behavior I did not like.<br>Last night is the most we have ever had show up for support team. We had alot of new faces and also those who have continued to support KGoC events over and over.<br><br>The <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> attitude</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> of the support team should be first and foremost to &quot;support&quot; the raiders, not for loot. But I also feel that they sacrifice enough to be given an option to lotto on dragon loot. I usually KNOW my support team and they have come to more than one raid with me. I am also willing to give those I don't know a fair chance. So at this point it comes to a matter of <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> trust</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->. I trust my support team to roll on items that they <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> need</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> and not just something they will give away, sell, or can get from another source. This shows <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> respect</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> for your fellow players. <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  Support team will still be able to lotto for items.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><br>As far as support team bringing alts and rolling, it has always had to be approved by the raid leader. For an example, one of our support/ buff team had a cleric for the raiding and a druid for the buffing. Obviously clerics are very important to a raid. But last night we were in need of a druid to cast Circle of Summer. So she toggled between two toons. Usually in cases as this, the player may chose to roll for either the cleric OR the druid, but not both. And the toon they are rolling for HAS to be involved in the raid in some way.. either as support or raider. This actually occurs quite often but ALWAYS has to be approved by the raid leader ahead of time.<br><br>I always try to be unbiased and fair, and not showing any favoritism. I listen to people's concerns and post when necessary. Periodically I do review the loot rules, strategys, buff line up, etc... things to improve the overall experience yet keeping in mind with the <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> true spirit</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> of the KCoG. <br><br>Lady Azure Skyeshadow<br>GL Mist Walkers<br>KCoG Dragon Raid Liason <p><br><br><center><img src="http://www.coastnet.com/~drake/EQ/Sigs/newsig.jpg"></center> </p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ueqkommisar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>eqkommisar</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Can-Head</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 6:19:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=11>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.chrometiger.com/~anubis/stuff/canhead.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Support Team and Raids</span><hr size=1> This is gonna be a kinda long post, too... some of it will be repeating what Azure has already said, but I think it's worth reading anyway.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br><br>First and foremost I'd like to apologize to Farrnusno for not being there.  I had RL obligations and was not able to attend.  I don't know that me being there would have made that much of a difference, however...  who knows.<br><br>When a new (or substitute) leader steps into someone's shoes, especially someone who's done as good a job as Azure has, there's always a &quot;getting to know you&quot; period of time - when raiders are getting used to how the new leader operates, and the new leader is getting a feel for how and when they need to do what.  That can be a painful period, and it is really up to the old veterans of many raids in the past to try and keep things running smoothly.  A few well chosen words from a known and respected name can usually calm a lot of people down.<br><br>When I started leading, most of the regulars already knew me because I'd been admin on Lagdalen's raids previously... so I really didn't have that much problem with people second guessing me or giving me problems...  I also had the priceless support of the uncanny and unflappable Kellory, who was stepping in to lead planes at the same time.<br><br>I generally brought along (up to) a single group of 53+ support people for buffing and giant clearing.  They were usually people I knew or had been on multiple raids with me in the past.  I also never brought more than a full group of 53+ support personnel.  Frankly, if a single group of 53+'ers isn't capable of handling the giant pulling/clearing and buffline duties... they are the wrong people or the wrong classes.<br><br>That being said, I was always grateful to have those that did come along to help, and I always let them roll if they wanted to.<br><br>But here are some guidelines for raid behavior, as I've learned them from my own and others raids (and from my own mistakes) in the past:<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As a leader:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Stand firm and don't take crap from anyone.  If someone questions your authority or your decisions openly... well, they obviously know enough to run the raid themselves, right?  They can bloody well sign their guild up on KGC on the rotations and do it themselves.  &lt;insert comment about a Paladin (gasp!) being main assist here&gt;<br>People wanna come on YOUR raid, they play by YOUR rules.  Period.<br>On the other hand... listen to your veterans.  Even after running countless raids, I still occasionally forgot things.  There is no point in having a good admin team if you don't listen to them.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As a veteran raider:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Support the leader in every way you can... and if you see something seriously wrong, give them a tell and let them know your concerns are.  An actual quote from me (though not on a KCoG raid... heh): You told &lt;raid leader&gt;, &quot;Hey, uh... the lair spawns are still up... we might want to pull them out and kill them before we charge in after Vox...&quot;. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>But whatever you do, never, ever, under any circumstances, question the raid leader on an open channel.<br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>    As a first time or reletively new raider:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br>Trust your leader and the admin to know their jobs.  If you have never actually been there and done that, no matter how many message boards and strategy discussions you've read, you probably don't have much of a clue about what needs to happen.  So strap in, settle down, shut up, and do what you are told.  Anything else is just going to make the raid take longer, and make you look like an a**hole.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->    <br>That sounds kind of harsh, but it's true.  Until you've actually coordinated pulling giants out of the lair with a dragon in it, or run a buff-line, or been in a leadership position and been getting so many tells that your text window is scrolling faster than a epic monks combat-spam... you really don't know what it takes.<br><br>There is no experience in the game that is analogous enough to fully prepare you for the burden of leading 50-60 people from so many different guilds with so wide a variety of skill and experience levels as come on KCoG raids.  If you've actually been there, then you should know better than to make trouble any.  If you haven't been there, you have no background from which to make any judgements. <p><img src=http://www.chrometiger.com/~anubis/stuff/kommisig.gif border=0 height=200 width=400><br>-Kommisar Nils "Can-Head" Hansen -- Guild Officer. Master Smith. Tank.KCoG Dragon Liason - retired (really!)</p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ueqkommisar.showPublicProfile?language=EN>eqkommisar</A> at: 6/30/02 6:22:46 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulogan42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Logan42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(6/30/02 7:34:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=12>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Clarification</span><hr size=1> Let me clarify a few points made in post from last night (after the raid when I was tired).<br><br>First of all, I do not have a problem with support people rolling.  As has been posted before and will be posted again without the support group (both with buffs and clearing) you can just go ahead and add 3 4 hours to the length of any KCoG dragon raid, and reduce the chance of success by about 40%.  Simple as that, they come and help us out tremendously, even if they don't directly help take out the dragon it would be MUCH harder for us to do it without them.  Any problem that I have is with the attitudes of said people coming and the sheer amounts.  At one point I near the beginning of the raid when people were just showing up we had around 50 people in EF, and 18 of them were 53+!  Now I appreciate that most of them did not roll on most of the items, and they helped out a good bit.  <br><br>But seriously do we need almost half of the people that show up to be support?  Do we need people among those that blatantly state that they are there to roll on the loot?  Believe me, if I had been more than a temporary standin for Azure I think some things might have changed pretty quick.  If I had felt it my place to do it I would have told Steelheart to pick his group, and sent the others off, for as much as we need support we don't need half of the 53+ people on the server running support for us, especially when they say in open channel (as I noticed several of them did, especially at the end of the raid) that they were just here for the roll on possible epic items.  If you do not feel any other call than the loot, or if that is your main reason for being there then I could live without seeing you there.  That said if you are coming to help out and have fun, and if you happen to win something that would work too, then that is great.  I do not have a problem with support rolling as long as the spirit of KCoG is upheld (and Azure has always done a great job of making sure that we walk that fine line, as have all of the previous raid leaders)<br><br>I do want to recognize those people that came to help out, and asked nothing in return.  There were several, and unfortunately I was too busy to take names of those people, but let me say that people like you are appreciated and the reason an organization like KCoG can exist.<br><br>As for the people switching alts in, I really do not like that.  I said it in my first post and I will say it again.  I am not going to name the names (it is a moot point anyway), but two people (actual 40 52 raiders, not support group) switched over to paladins just so that they could roll on the book.  These were not asked to bring one over the other, and this was not a case of being an exception.  At the time I (as in just about every other point during the night) was holding 5 10 conversations and I had not researched past history at that point, and had no time to ask Azure about how she handles this (besides which she was probably as bad off at that point as I was, while she was commanding the buffline).  As such I decided not to rock the boat and did not prevent it from happening.  Looking back in my log to how it went down it was obvious from their tones in /tells that they were taking advantage of the fact that I was new to leading vox, and decided to run over me.  Now that I have had time to look over the circumstances, and graze through old conversations on the board, as well as Azure's statement I would say that that is the one thing about last night that I would like to take back and redo.  It is moot because a book did not even drop, but it is kind of a point of pride for the KCoG and to allow that kind of stuff to go on leaves a slight bad taste in my mouth.<br><br>All that said any changes to be made, or rules to be clarified are Azure's to do.  It is her place as the KCoG Dragon Raid Liason to make decisions like this, and no matter what decisions they are I for one will support her.  She has always done a great job, and until she tires of the experience she will continue to do a great job.  And to be truthful, if I never got to roll on an item again, I would still show up to as many as I possibly could, and I hope that most of you can say that honestly as well.  Something you might want to think about.<br><br>-Far