tab.gif"></center></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulagdalentarcho.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Lagdalen Tarcho</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoG Companion</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(7/1/02 1:08:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=15>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.engtong.com/Valoran/images/60x60/lagdalen60x60.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Addition</span><hr size=1> /rampages<br><br>I help with mod rods when I am able to help out CoG so I go when I can. And whomever EDITED is, I want a word with you and me and my pet in a dark back alley... <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CBC6B1><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uhaemish.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Haemish</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalBlack.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>KCoG Founder</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(7/1/02 9:45:40 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm8.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=244.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.godwinclients.com/sd/haemish_new.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Addition</span><hr size=1> Woof, what a thing to come back to on Monday morning. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <br><br>I'll reiterate some things already said here, and provide some real history that stretches back past Lagdalen's time as leader (yes, there was Everquest before then). Damn younguns! :P<br><br>KCoG was NOT created just to do dragon raids and planes raids for people who couldn't otherwise do them. It was created to do things that did not involve raiding, items, experience gathering or loot at all, because it seemed that the attitude of the server community was focusing on those things alone, and forgetting things like roleplaying, togetherness and pure fun. I gathered together the leaders of as many guilds on the server as would come to create a very loose organization that would provide support to anyone on the server willing to do player-driven events for anyone, regardless of guild affiliation. Things like roleplaying storylines, arena tournaments, silly Valentine Dances and Naked Ogre Relay Races. In time, I hit upon the idea of Mixer Hunts, which would gather large scale raid bodies together from any guilds as training/preparation for doing large scale raids such as dragon and planes raids. Learning the discipline needed by raiders, as well as by leaders was what those were all about. <br><br>Soon after that, Jzonn and Ikada of (at the time) the Avenging Crusaders asked if they could use the KCoG platform to try to run dragon raids, and Zellex of the Watchmen asked if he could lead a KCoG raid into the Plane of Fear. Why? Because they wanted to, and because their respective guilds wanted to learn how to run these things for their own guilds. At first, I was hesitant, because these things can often be very loot centric. But I decided in the long run, providing this kind of opportunity to those who were not currently Karana Guild Central (not Karana Council of Guilds) members (which at the time was composed of less than 20 guilds), was exactly what the KCoG was about. Providing experiences led by other players. So they went ahead and tried them. <br><br>It took a while before we got our first win against a dragon, Nagafen. A lot of folks died trying to beat that dragon. Zellex had some successes and some failures with planes raids. After 6 months to a year of these guys running the raids, I decided to bring my own alliance (Sacred Band) in to help run them. Zellex and the SB raid teams began jointly running the planes raids, and Jzonn had decided to stop running the dragon raids. It was during this time that I decided, as raid leader, to restrict the dragon raids to only those players who were level 52 and under. There was no support team, and I didn't figure on anyone over 52 wanting to come help out on the raids, since they couldn't fight. So it wasn't really an issue of support teams rollilng. After about 6 months, I decided it was time for the SB alliance to do their own raids, and stepped down from leading CoG raid events. Soon after, Lagdalen took up the slack. <br><br>Lagdalen first asked me if I'd considered using support groups of 53+, and after having done that with the SB alliance, I agreed it was a good idea. Why? Because KCoG dragon raids took as long as 7 hours, and if we messed up and died, we usually needed 53+ support to help us recover bodies. With a good support team of even 1 group of 53+ folks, the giants dropped like flies, cutting at the very least 1 hour off of the raids. Making raids like this shorter is a good thing, especially when they come on weeknights. Those people who come to fight the giants and help in the buffline give up their time just like anyone under 53, and they can die just as easily against the giants, losing experience (which translates to time) just like anyone else. You bleed, you roll has always been one of my strongest beliefs with loot. It isn't always literal, as some things get restricted by class, but the spirit is there. <br><br><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> If the raid is being done for the experience (the kind that doesn't show up in your experience bar) and the fun, everyone deserves a chance to get some reward. </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--><br><br>Does the CoG need 18 people 53+ to do the raid? No, technically it doesn't need any 53+ folks, but it sure makes the raid go smoother, and recovery go quicker. Given that the raid leader will probably spend at least 1-3 hours more time setting up before and cleaning up after the raid, anything that cuts his/her time down is a definite boon. It's up to the raid leader to decide whether to use the support people, and the raid leader CAN restrict them from rolling, if he or she wishes. I'd hope they wouldn't, except in extreme circumstances, and I'd hope any support person that came would take whatever decision was made in stride. Azure's post hit the nail on the head about respect, trust and what she expects, and I'd suggest that anyone that has a problem with my message reread hers.<br><br>Finally, to EDITED, whoever he or she may be, please, don't come back to a CoG raid. That kind of attitude not only is not wanted or needed, it is totally counter to the reason the raids are being run. While I don't necessarily agree with people using an open channel to tell you off, hearing STFU was certainly what you needed and deserved. It might have been harsher than what I'd have told you in a open channel, but it's message would have been the same. My message would have read, &quot;This is not the place to equip you, to ensure your epic, or to fill your coffers. This is the place to have fun. If you did not have fun doing this raid, I suggest you not return to another COG raid, as you won't get anything more out of this type of raid.&quot;<br><br>Sorry for the history lesson, folks, but sometimes it helps to know what has gone before so as to avoid repeating mistakes in the future. <p>Haemish MacLennan<br>Founder<Br>Karana Council of Guilds<br>"I don't play role-playing games to be a politician."</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#FFFFCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/ulogan42.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Logan42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#8E9173>(7/1/02 11:35:22 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub6.ezboard.com/fcouncilofguildsfrm